Hi @kramer65, in this case you need to create your own _CSShake_ animation, and for its purpose you have the `do-shake` mixin. After you clone the repo `git clone https://github.com/elrumordelaluz/csshake.git`, install the basic packages `npm install` (you need [npm installed](https://docs.npmjs.com/cli/install) on your system) and you could start trying what you want with the Sass stuff. 
Try something like 

``` scss
.shake-horizontal-chunk { 
  @include do-shake('shake-horizontal-chunk', 30, 0, 0, 4s, $chunk: 40%); 
}
```

in the `csshake.scss` file and then run `npm run build:raw` or `npm run build:min`.
Keep in mind that the whole code generated in _CSShake_ is based on `random` generated numbers between the values you use in the `mixin`. For a detailed exmplanation of the mixin, read more [here](https://github.com/elrumordelaluz/csshake#customize)

Hi @elrumordelaluz thing is that I am using [css-modules](https://github.com/css-modules/css-modules). So I am not able to simply write something like `class="shake-constant"` in my markup. Also all my class names will be hashed on deployment and I do not load any plain CSS files from my server. So what I basically do (in the project using my fork) is:

``` scss
@import "../../../node_modules/csshake/scss/csshake";

.callToActionShaking {
  @extend .callToAction;
  @extend .shake-constant;

  display: block;
}
```

That's why I need `shake-constant` to be defined ;-)

@seb0zz you could do one of this two things:

``` scss
@import "../../../node_modules/csshake/scss/csshake";
.yourClass {
  @extend .shake.shake-constant;
  ...
}
```

or 

``` scss
@import "../../../node_modules/csshake/scss/csshake";

%myAnim { @include do-shake(); }
.yourClass {
  @extend %myAnim.shake-constant;
  ...
}
```

